<HEADLINE>
<P>
PUC ADOPTS UTILITY DISCOUNTS FOR NEEDY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The California Public Utilities Commission on Wednesday voted to create a 
program to provide low-income residential utility customers with discounted gas 
and electric rates, as ordered by a state law passed earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
The commission's vote set eligibility requirements for customers to qualify for 
the discounts, which are expected to become effective Nov. 1, the beginning of 
the winter heating season. 
</P>
<P>
The commission will decide the actual amount of the discounts at a meeting in 
September, a spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
To qualify for the discounts, a customer's household income cannot exceed 
certain levels. For most utility customers, eligibility would be limited to 
households with an annual income of no more than $13,000 for one to two people, 
$15,200 for three people, $18,300 for four people and $3,000 more for each 
additional person. 
</P>
<P>
Utilities will begin notifying customers of the program in August and September 
bill inserts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
