<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
BASKETBALL DRAFT TO CONTINUE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
COLUMBUS, Ohio 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Owners of the 16 teams in the Continental Basketball Assn. decided today to 
continue with the scheduled two-day draft, even though the plane crash in Sioux 
City, Iowa, has cast a pall over the activities. 
</P>
<P>
Commissioner Jay Ramsdel, 25, and his deputy commissioner, Jerry Schemmel, were 
flying from the league's headquarters in Denver to Columbus aboard the United 
DC-10 that crashed Wednesday in Iowa. Schemmel was listed as one of the 
survivors, but Ramsdel was still missing as of this afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
"The crash will have no effect on the operations of the draft," said Tim Sise, 
general manager of the Columbus Horizon. "Tonight we're looking at some of the 
best basketball players, and to halt the growth of the league is something he 
(Ramsdel) wouldn't have wanted." 
</P>
</TEXT>
